04723nam a22008055i 9780231518253DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2009    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315182537 a10.7312/mcna145022doi  a(DE-B1597)459121  a(OCoLC)774288700  a(OCoLC)979620235  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aE99.C6bM346 2009 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a305.8972221 aMcNally, Michael D., eauthor.10aHonoring Elders :bAging, Authority, and Ojibwe Religion /cMichael D. McNally. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource :b22 halftones, 0 color illus., 0 line drawings, 0 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligion and American Culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Aging and the Life Cycle Imagined in Ojibwe Tradition and Lived in History -- t2. Eldership, Respect, and the Sacred Community -- t3. Elders as Grandparents and Teachers -- t4. Elders Articulating Tradition -- t5. The Sacralization of Eldership -- t6. The Shape of Wisdom -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLike many Native Americans, Ojibwe people esteem the wisdom, authority, and religious significance of old age, but this respect does not come easily or naturally. It is the fruit of hard work, rooted in narrative traditions, moral vision, and ritualized practices of decorum that are comparable in sophistication to those of Confucianism. Even as the dispossession and policies of assimilation have threatened Ojibwe peoplehood and have targeted the traditions and the elders who embody it, Ojibwe and other Anishinaabe communities have been resolute and resourceful in their disciplined respect for elders. Indeed, the challenges of colonization have served to accentuate eldership in new ways.Using archival and ethnographic research, Michael D. McNally follows the making of Ojibwe eldership, showing that deference to older women and men is part of a fuller moral, aesthetic, and cosmological vision connected to the ongoing circle of lifea tradition of authority that has been crucial to surviving colonization. McNally argues that the tradition of authority and the authority of tradition frame a decidedly indigenous dialectic, eluding analytic frameworks of invented tradition and naïve continuity. Demonstrating the rich possibilities of treating age as a category of analysis, McNally provocatively asserts that the elder belongs alongside the priest, prophet, sage, and other key figures in the study of religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aOjibwa IndiansxReligion. 0aOjibwa IndiansxSocial life and customs. 0aOlder Ojibwa Indians. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045952440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/mcna14502423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231518253.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013  a978-3-11-045952-4  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066254-2  CUP eBook Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG